<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between old-vine Zinfandel and regular Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Old-vine Zinfandel comes from grapevines that are typically 50+ years old, producing smaller yields of more concentrated fruit with deeper complexity and minerality. These wines often display more refined tannins, layered flavors of dark fruit and spice, and better aging potential compared to younger vine Zinfandel. The best old-vine Zinfandels come from historic vineyards in Dry Creek Valley, Paso Robles, and Lodi, where some vines date back to the 1880s.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Zinfandel good for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Zinfandel is excellent for beginners due to its approachable fruit-forward character and food-friendly nature. The best entry-level Zinfandels from producers like Bogle, Ravenswood, or 14 Hands offer ripe berry flavors, moderate tannins, and typically 14-15% alcohol that won't overwhelm new wine drinkers. Unlike complex Bordeaux blends or austere Burgundies, Zinfandel's jammy fruit character and spicy finish are immediately appealing and pair well with familiar foods like barbecue and pizza.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve the best Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Zinfandel slightly below room temperature at 60-65°F (15-18°C) to best showcase its fruit character while taming the alcohol heat. This temperature range allows the wine's blackberry and spice notes to shine without the jammy flavors becoming overpowering. Avoid serving too warm (above 70°F), which can make high-alcohol Zinfandels taste harsh and unbalanced, or too cold (below 55°F), which mutes the wine's signature bold fruit expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can you age the best Zinfandel wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Zinfandels from top producers like Ridge, Turley, or Rafanelli can age gracefully for 8-15 years, developing tertiary flavors of leather, tobacco, and dried herbs. However, most Zinfandels are crafted for earlier consumption and are best enjoyed within 3-5 years of vintage to preserve their vibrant fruit character. The key indicators for aging potential include balanced acidity, structured tannins, and alcohol levels below 15.5% - wines exceeding this alcohol threshold often lack the structure for long-term cellaring.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value region for quality Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Paso Robles offers the best value for quality Zinfandel, producing wines with the concentration and complexity of premium Sonoma bottlings at 30-40% lower prices. The region's diverse soils and warm days with cool nights create ideal conditions for Zinfandel, with producers like J. Lohr, Epoch, and Chronic Cellars delivering exceptional wines under $25. Lodi also provides excellent value, particularly for everyday drinking Zinfandels that showcase pure varietal character without breaking the bank.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are common mistakes when buying Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing Zinfandels with excessive alcohol levels (16%+), which often taste hot and unbalanced, masking the wine's natural fruit character. Many buyers also confuse White Zinfandel with red Zinfandel - they're completely different styles from the same grape, with White Zin being a sweet, light rosé. Additionally, avoid assuming all California Zinfandels taste the same; regional differences between Dry Creek Valley's spicy elegance and Paso Robles' bold fruit intensity are significant and worth exploring.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Zinfandel if I can't find a good bottle?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Côtes du Rhône from France offers similar spicy, medium-bodied characteristics with Grenache-based blends that mirror Zinfandel's pepper and dark fruit notes. Australian Shiraz provides comparable bold fruit intensity and approachable tannins, particularly bottlings from McLaren Vale or Barossa Valley. For domestic alternatives, look for Petite Sirah for more structure and intensity, or Rhône-style blends from California that often include Zinfandel's genetic cousin, the Italian Primitivo grape.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Do I need to decant the best Zinfandel wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most modern Zinfandels don't require decanting since they're typically made in a fruit-forward, accessible style with soft tannins. However, decanting can benefit high-end, age-worthy Zinfandels from producers like Ridge Geyserville or Turley Estate, allowing 30-60 minutes of air contact to soften intense tannins and integrate alcohol. Young, powerful Zinfandels with 15%+ alcohol particularly benefit from brief decanting to mellow the heat and allow the fruit character to emerge more elegantly.</p>
